<div class="question">
<h3>Exam Question</h3>

<p>
Consider the expression $-5-6x-x^2$.
</p>

<p>
(a) Write the expression in the form $q-(x+p)^2$.
</p>

<p>
(b) Hence write down the coordinates of the turning point of
$y=-5-6x-x^2$.
</p>

</div>


<div class="solution">
<h3>Solution</h3>

<p>First rewrite the quadratic:</p>

$$y=-x^2-6x-5$$

<p>Factor out $-1$:</p>

$$y=-(x^2+6x)-5$$

<p>Complete the square:</p>

$$x^2+6x=(x+3)^2-9$$

<p>Substitute:</p>

$$y=-[(x+3)^2-9]-5$$

<p>Simplify:</p>

$$y=4-(x+3)^2$$

<p>The turning point is <strong>$(-3,4)$</strong>.</p>

</div>


